\b\fs36\par
\fs28 Atlas Free Clusters: \fs36\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs28 Logical Size is: \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if the total size of the data and indexes is outside the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\fs24             Applicable for Atlas Free Clusters Only\par
\b\fs28 Memory : \b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure memory for a MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's mem document. You can view these metrics on the Atlas Memory and Non-Mapped Virtual Memory charts, accessed through cluster monitoring.\b\fs36\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs28 Memory: Resident is : \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if the size of the resident memory meets the specified threshold. It is typical over time, on a dedicated database server, for the size of the resident memory to approach the amount of physical RAM on the box.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 Memory: Virtual is: \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if the size of virtual memory for the mongod process meets the specified threshold. You can use this alert to flag excessive memory outside of memory mapping.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 Memory: Computed is : \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if the size of virtual memory that is not accounted for by memory-mapping meets the specified threshold. If this number is very high (multiple gigabytes), it indicates that excessive memory is being used outside of memory mapping.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 System Memory: Used is : \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if system memory usage meets the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 System Memory: \b0\fs24 Max Used is : Sends an alert if the maximum system memory usage value meets the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 System Memory: \b0\fs24 Free is : Sends an alert if the amount of free system memory drops below the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 System Memory: \b0\fs24 Max Free is : Sends an alert if the maximum amount of free system memory drops below the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 System Memory: \b0\fs24 Available is : Sends an alert if the amount of available system memory drops below the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 System Memory: \b0\fs24 Max Available is : Sends an alert if the maximum amount of available system memory drops below the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs28 DB Storage:\b0\fs24 The following alert conditions apply to database storage, as collected for a MongoDB process by the MongoDB dbStats command. \par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\fs28 DB Storage is: \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if the allocated storage meets the specified threshold. This alert condition can be viewed on a host's DB Storage chart, accessed through cluster monitoring.\b\fs36\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs28 DB Data Size is: \b0\fs24 Sends an alert if approximate size of all documents (and their paddings) meets the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs28 Restarts\fs36\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs28 Restarts in Last Hour is:\b0\fs24 Sends an alert if the number of times a host restarts within the previous hour exceeds the specified threshold.\b\fs36\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs28 Asserts:\b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure the rate of asserts for a MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's asserts document. You can view asserts through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Atlas Search: \b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure the amount of CPU and memory used by Atlas Search processes. You can view Atlas Search metrics through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Average Execution Time:\b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure the average execution time of reads, writes, or commands for a MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's opLatencies document. You can view asserts through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Opcounter:\b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure the rate of database operations on a MongoDB process since the process last started, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's opcounters document. You can view opcounters through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Connections: \b0\fs24 The following alert condition measures connections to a MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's connections document. You can view this metric on the Atlas Connections chart, accessed through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Queues: \b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure operations waiting on locks, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's globalLock document. You can view these metrics on the Atlas Queues chart, accessed through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Page Faults: \b0\fs24 The following alert condition measures the rate of page faults for a MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's extra_info.page_faults field.\par
\b\fs28 Cursors: \b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure the number of cursors for a MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's metrics.cursor document. You can view these metrics on the Atlas Cursors chart, accessed through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 Network:\b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure throughput for MongoDB process, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's network document. You can view these metrics on a host's Network chart, accessed through cluster monitoring.\par
\b\fs28 System and Disk Alerts\par
Opcounter - Repl:\b0\fs24 The following alert conditions measure the rate of database operations on MongoDB secondaries, as collected from the MongoDB serverStatus command's opcountersRepl document. You can view these metrics on the Opcounters - Repl chart, accessed through cluster monitoring.\par

